    <section class="analysis-section">
      <h2>Species Profiles & Analysis</h2>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>African Elephant</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 60-70 years</p>
        <p>The largest terrestrial animal on Earth. African elephants are distinguished by their massive size, highly dexterous trunk, and large ears shaped like the continent of Africa. They possess remarkable intelligence, complex social structures led by a matriarch, and exhibit behaviors indicating grief and deep memory. Studying the african elephant provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Bald Eagle</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Aves | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 20-30 years</p>
        <p>A majestic bird of prey found in North America and the national symbol of the United States. Characterized by a white head and tail contrasting with a dark brown body, they build massive nests near large bodies of open water and feed primarily on fish. Studying the bald eagle provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Blue Whale</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 80-90 years</p>
        <p>The largest known animal to have ever lived, exceeding even the dinosaurs in sheer mass. Despite their gargantuan size, reaching up to 100 feet long, blue whales feed almost exclusively on tiny, shrimp-like krill, consuming tons every single day. Studying the blue whale provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Cheetah</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 10-12 years</p>
        <p>The fastest land animal, capable of reaching speeds up to 70 mph in short bursts. Built for extraordinary acceleration, they have a slender frame, non-retractable claws for traction, and a flexible spine that acts like a spring during high-speed pursuits. Studying the cheetah provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Emperor Penguin</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Aves | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 15-20 years</p>
        <p>The tallest and heaviest of all living penguin species. Emperor penguins endure the brutal Antarctic winter to breed, forming massive huddles to survive temperatures plummeting to -40°C. Males heroically incubate the single egg on their feet for months while fasting. Studying the emperor penguin provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Galapagos Tortoise</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Reptilia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 100+ years</p>
        <p>Giant tortoises endemic to the volcanic Galapagos Islands. Famous for their immense size and incredible longevity, some individuals have lived well past 150 years. Their distinct shell shapes played a role in Charles Darwin's development of evolutionary theory. Studying the galapagos tortoise provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Giant Panda</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 20 years</p>
        <p>Iconic bears native to South Central China, easily recognized by their bold black-and-white coat. Despite having a digestive system classified as carnivorous, their diet consists almost entirely of bamboo, requiring them to consume massive amounts daily for energy. Studying the giant panda provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Giraffe</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 25 years</p>
        <p>The tallest living terrestrial animal, native to Africa. Their incredibly long necks and legs evolved to allow them to browse foliage high in the acacia trees, out of reach of most other herbivores. They have uniquely patterned coats and prehensile tongues. Studying the giraffe provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Gorilla</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 35-40 years</p>
        <p>The largest living primates, inhabiting the tropical forests of central Sub-Saharan Africa. They are largely herbivorous, highly social, ground-dwelling apes living in troops led by a dominant silverback male. They share a high percentage of their DNA with humans. Studying the gorilla provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Great White Shark</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Chondrichthyes | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 70+ years</p>
        <p>An apex marine predator renowned for its size, power, and role in balancing ocean ecosystems. Equipped with rows of serrated teeth and an acute sense of smell, they are highly migratory and capable of spectacular breaching behaviors while hunting. Studying the great white shark provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Green Sea Turtle</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Reptilia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 80+ years</p>
        <p>A large sea turtle found globally in tropical and subtropical waters. Named not for its shell, but for the greenish color of its fat, they migrate long distances between feeding grounds and the exact beaches where they hatched decades prior to lay their eggs. Studying the green sea turtle provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Grizzly Bear</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Omnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 20-25 years</p>
        <p>A large subspecies of brown bear inhabiting North America. Characterized by a distinctive muscular shoulder hump, grizzlies are powerful and adaptable foragers, heavily reliant on salmon runs and berries to accumulate fat stores before winter hibernation. Studying the grizzly bear provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Hippopotamus</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 40-50 years</p>
        <p>Large, mostly herbivorous, semi-aquatic mammals inhabiting sub-Saharan Africa. Despite their stocky build and short legs, they are highly aggressive and incredibly fast on land. They spend their days wallowing in water or mud to keep cool. Studying the hippopotamus provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Kangaroo</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 15-20 years</p>
        <p>Large marsupials endemic to Australia, defined by their powerful hind legs designed for leaping, large feet, and long muscular tails for balance. Females have a forward-opening pouch where their embryonic young, or joeys, complete postnatal development. Studying the kangaroo provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Komodo Dragon</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Reptilia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 30 years</p>
        <p>The largest living species of lizard, found on several Indonesian islands. They are apex predators in their ecosystems, armed with venomous saliva, serrated teeth, and the ability to consume massive quantities of meat in a single feeding. Studying the komodo dragon provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Moose</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 15-20 years</p>
        <p>The largest and heaviest extant species in the deer family, found in the boreal and mixed deciduous forests of the Northern Hemisphere. Males are instantly recognizable by their immense, broad, palmate antlers, which they shed and regrow annually. Studying the moose provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Orangutan</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Omnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 35-45 years</p>
        <p>Highly intelligent great apes native to the rainforests of Borneo and Sumatra. They are primarily arboreal, spending most of their time in the canopy. Known for their distinctive red hair and exceptional problem-solving abilities, they face severe threats from habitat loss. Studying the orangutan provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Ostrich</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Aves | <strong>Diet:</strong> Omnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 40-45 years</p>
        <p>The largest and heaviest living bird, native to Africa. Flightless but incredibly swift, ostriches can sprint up to 43 mph. They lay the largest eggs of any living land animal and have powerful legs capable of delivering lethal defensive kicks. Studying the ostrich provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Platypus</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 10-15 years</p>
        <p>A highly unusual, semi-aquatic mammal endemic to eastern Australia. It is one of the few living monotremes—mammals that lay eggs instead of giving birth to live young. They possess a duck-like bill, beaver-like tail, webbed feet, and venomous spurs (in males). Studying the platypus provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Polar Bear</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 25-30 years</p>
        <p>The largest extant land carnivore, heavily adapted to the frigid Arctic environment. Their thick layer of blubber and dense fur provide vital insulation. They rely almost entirely on sea ice as a platform for hunting ringed and bearded seals. Studying the polar bear provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Rhinoceros</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 40-50 years</p>
        <p>Massive herbivores characterized by their large size, thick skin, and distinct horns made of keratin. Several species exist across Africa and Asia. Despite their intimidating appearance, they are primarily grazers and browsers, heavily targeted by poachers. Studying the rhinoceros provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Saltwater Crocodile</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Reptilia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 70+ years</p>
        <p>The largest living reptile, found in estuarine and coastal regions of the Indo-Pacific. They are formidable apex ambush predators capable of taking down massive prey. They have the strongest recorded bite force of any animal currently alive. Studying the saltwater crocodile provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Siberian Tiger</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 10-15 years</p>
        <p>Also known as the Amur tiger, it is the largest of the tiger subspecies. Adapted to the harsh, snowy environments of the Russian Far East, they possess a thick coat and a layer of fat. They are solitary apex predators requiring vast territories to survive. Studying the siberian tiger provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Sloth</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Herbivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 20-30 years</p>
        <p>Arboreal mammals native to Central and South America, notorious for their exceptionally slow movements. This extreme sluggishness is a metabolic adaptation to their low-energy diet of leaves. Their fur often hosts symbiotic algae, providing camouflage. Studying the sloth provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card data-row-details">
        <h3>Snow Leopard</h3>
        <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Mammalia | <strong>Diet:</strong> Carnivore | <strong>Lifespan:</strong> 15-18 years</p>
        <p>Elusive big cats native to the rugged, mountainous regions of Central and South Asia. Known as the 'ghost of the mountains,' they are perfectly adapted to the cold with incredibly thick fur and a long, thick tail used for balance and warmth. Studying the snow leopard provides crucial insights into evolutionary adaptation and the delicate balance required to maintain healthy ecosystems. As environmental pressures mount globally, understanding the specific needs and behaviors of these species becomes increasingly vital for ongoing conservation efforts.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is a list of animals?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">A list of animals categorizes different species from across the globe based on taxonomy, habitat, diet, or other characteristics. It helps organize the massive biodiversity found on Earth, ranging from mammals and birds to reptiles and amphibians.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the largest animal in the world?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">The Blue Whale is definitively the largest animal to have ever existed on Earth. These incredible marine mammals can reach lengths of over 100 feet and weigh upwards of 150 tons, making them significantly larger than any known dinosaur.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the fastest land animal?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">The Cheetah holds the title of the fastest land animal. Built for explosive acceleration, a cheetah can reach top speeds of roughly 70 mph (112 km/h) in short bursts when hunting prey on the African savanna.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Are there mammals that lay eggs?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Yes, mammals that lay eggs are called monotremes. There are only five living species of monotremes in the world: the unique duck-billed platypus and four species of echidnas, all of which are native to Australia and New Guinea.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How long do Galapagos tortoises live?</summary>
        <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Galapagos giant tortoises are famous for their incredible longevity. While their lifespan in the wild is estimated to be over 100 years, captive individuals have been documented living well past 150 years, with some unverified claims reaching 175 years.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    // Search functionality
    const searchInput = document.getElementById('searchInput');
    const tableRows = document.querySelectorAll('.data-row');
    const detailCards = document.querySelectorAll('.data-row-details');

    searchInput.addEventListener('input', function(e) {
      const term = e.target.value.toLowerCase();

      tableRows.forEach((row, index) => {
        const text = row.textContent.toLowerCase();
        const detailText = detailCards[index].textContent.toLowerCase();

        if (text.includes(term) || detailText.includes(term)) {
          row.style.display = '';
          detailCards[index].style.display = '';
        } else {
          row.style.display = 'none';
          detailCards[index].style.display = 'none';
        }
      });
    });

    // Sort functionality
    let sortAsc = true;
    function sortTable(colIndex) {
      const table = document.getElementById("dataTable");
      const tbody = table.tBodies[0];
      const rows = Array.from(tbody.querySelectorAll("tr"));

      sortAsc = !sortAsc;

      rows.sort((a, b) => {
        let valA = a.cells[colIndex].textContent.trim();
        let valB = b.cells[colIndex].textContent.trim();

        return sortAsc ? valA.localeCompare(valB) : valB.localeCompare(valA);
      });

      rows.forEach(row => tbody.appendChild(row));
    }
  </script>
